<text>Selecting, translating and rotating multiple atoms

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

In the last section, we learned that an atom can be dragged within an assisting plane or a plane parallel to it. In this section, we will learn two other ways of changing the coordinates of an atom.

Using keyboard shortcuts to move an atom in a direction

   To move in the &quot;+x&quot; or &quot;-x&quot; direction, hold down the &apos;x&apos; key and press the Up/Down key.
   To move in the &quot;+y&quot; or &quot;-y&quot; direction, hold down the &apos;x&apos; key and press the Up/Down key.
   To move in the &quot;+z&quot; or &quot;-z&quot; direction, hold down the &apos;x&apos; key and press the Up/Down key.

To know the direction, look at the axes at the lower-right corner. The x-axis is represented by a red arrow, which pointing to the &quot;+x&quot; direction. The y-axis is represented by a green arrow, which pointing to the &quot;+y&quot; direction. The z-axis is represented by a blue arrow, which pointing to the &quot;+z&quot; direction.

Typing the coordinates in the Properties Window

Right-click (or CTRL+click on Mac OS X without a multiple-button mouse) on the atom and select &quot;Properties&quot; from the pop-up menu. When the dialog window opens, type the new coordinates in the &quot;X&quot;, &quot;Y&quot;, &quot;Z&quot; text fields, respectively.

